East Texas Foundation Organizes Strategic Plan to Improve Early Literacy Education at Rural Schools

Educators know that newer approaches to teaching reading can get better results. But small schools can lack the training and resources they need to make changes.
by Lane Wendell Fischer January 22, 2024January 19, 2024

Share this:

  • Click to share on Facebook (Opens in new window)
  • Click to share on Twitter (Opens in new window)
  • Click to share on LinkedIn (Opens in new window)
  • Click to email a link to a friend (Opens in new window)

Like many schools across the nation, elementary students at Newton Independent School District, which covers 500 square miles in rural East Texas, were struggling to read.

Although their teachers were equipped with a scientifically supported reading curriculum that provided activities to test student progress, drive home important lessons, and target specific areas of weakness, students continued to score poorly in national assessments.

The problem was that Newton’s teachers didn’t receive the training they needed during their college years to teach this curriculum. And school administrators didn’t have the knowledge or tools to coach their teachers, said Michelle Barrow, superintendent of Newton schools.

“There was a lack of administrator training on what to look for and how to help the teachers,” she said in an interview with the Daily Yonder.

Newton isn’t the only school that’s faced an early literacy education crisis. Recent data from the Nation’s Report Card found that between 2019 and 2022, students across the country were reading at lower levels.

Thirty-five percent of rural fourth graders tested at a “below basic” reading level, which is a functionally illiterate reading level, according to National Association of Educational Procurement (NAEP) assessment standards. 

Lower-income, rural students are at greater risk. Nationally, 52% of students eligible for free or reduced-cost lunch scored below a basic reading level in 2022. In comparison, 24% of students who don’t qualify for free or reduced-cost lunch scored below a basic level.

At a school like Newton, a Title I school where all students receive free breakfast and lunch, it’s common that students lack books in the home, Barrow said. 

“You have to provide as much as you can at school,” she said. “You can’t penalize a kid when they don’t have a parent that can or will help them at home.”

A Three-Prong Approach

In June, 2022, the T.L.L. Temple Foundation announced that they would be investing more than $3 million to improve early literacy education across rural East Texas.

Education was an important topic to T.L.L. Temple, the family businessman and namesake of the foundation. It remains a strategic focus of the foundation’s century-old mission to build a thriving rural East Texas, said Wynn Rosser, president and CEO of the foundation.

The T.L.L. Temple Foundation partnered with three organizations to create a three-pronged program to improve teacher training and support, said Sylvia A. Leal, Ed.D., the foundation’s senior program officer of education and economic opportunity.

The first two prongs focus on future teachers. 

First, the foundation partnered with Deans for Impact, to provide early literacy education training to three local universities who produce the most future teachers for the region. 

Second, the foundation worked with TNTP (formerly known as The New Teacher Project) to provide this training for teachers who are coming to the classroom via “alternative certification programs,” which train teachers who are entering the profession from a non-education field. Most of the rural teachers in East Texas take this path.

“Alternative certification programs [can] have a reputation for being fast and cheap,” said Rosser in an interview with the Daily Yonder. 

The final prong focuses on supporting current teachers.

T.L.L. Temple teamed up with Instruction Partners, an organization that works directly with local school districts to help administrators and faculty succeed. 

Their work initially began with Newton and two other rural East Texas districts. In June, 2023, T.L.L. Temple announced another $1.4 million grant to take the organization to three additional schools.

Their goal is to train school leaders to coach teachers and organize planning meetings so that when Instruction Partners leaves the school, the faculty still have the support they need, said Ben Fenton, chief of growth and delivery at Instruction Partners.

“We really want to make sure those leaders have the understanding of instructional practices [and] know how to give feedback in those areas,” she said.

Rural-Specific Solutions

Instruction Partners, Deans for Impact, and TNTP all responded to an early call from the T.L.L. Temple Foundation. What started out as roundtable discussions about the foundation’s strategy to address the area’s early literacy crisis became a multi-million dollar project to address the issue from a rural angle.

“We were looking for someone who’s willing to roll up their sleeves and work with us and assist our superintendents to help us understand how [to] address early literacy in a small rural setting that’s very different from a large urban district, Rosser said.”

The larger problem across the country, in both rural and urban schools, is the widespread use of flawed early literacy curricula.

Recently, schools have been moving to an alternative science-backed curriculum called “The Science of Reading” that better teaches students foundational reading comprehension skills. 

Making the change to “The Science of Reading” curriculum isn’t easy, Fenton said. The curriculum requires more from teachers, who are expected to continually assess their students and quickly adapt their lessons to suit each student’s unique needs.

For larger schools with faculty dedicated to coaching teachers through these challenges, this kind of curriculum transition is an easier lift. For rural schools, it can be almost impossible.

“I think some of our teachers were lost,” Barrow said. “Sometimes you throw your hands up because you are so overwhelmed.”

Rural school leaders like Barrow often don’t have time to devote to teacher coaching because they already fill many roles in their school and community that their urban or suburban counterparts may not.

“We know a superintendent who is the superintendent, sometimes drives a bus, sometimes has to be the person that figures out how you get the bus unstuck on the red dirt road and flips burgers on a Friday night,” Rosser said. “She just doesn’t have the resources to devote to someone individually who would do each of these things in her district.”

To solve this rural-specific problem, the T.L.L. Temple Foundation employed a rural-specific solution by bringing in outside organizations to increase local capacity.

“[Bringing in outside organizations] respectfully is really important to us because we get condescended to a lot by our urban peers,” Rosser said. “We’re trying to do things in a very different context with very different resources.”

Periodically, the foundation brings all of the important players — foundation leaders, school administration, and support organization leaders — together to ensure that each piece of the puzzle is not only working on its own, but that they are working together.

For example, universities working with Deans for Impact will send their students to visit public schools that are partnered with Instruction Partners, so future teachers can see reading classes in action. This also allows university instructors to see what techniques work and don’t work in the classroom.

This interaction between the curriculum, university, and classroom levels is uncommon in the education field. It is rural ingenuity at its finest, and an important part of the foundation’s role, Rosser said.

Leveraging Local Relationships to Build Trust and Success

As T.L.L. Temple Foundation’s early literacy partnership program enters its second year, members found that one its greatest strengths is the foundation’s healthy relationship with local schools. 

When Instruction Partners sent a team to start working with Newton schools, staff were initially concerned by the hands-on approach from the outsider organization.

“There was a lot of uncertainty from staff,” Barrow said. “There’s some trust that had to be built.”

The foundation’s long track record in the region may help school leaders and community members trust its programs.

“I know from past experiences that T.L.L. Temple is very intentional about what they’re trying to do in our area,” Barrow said. “I know when they bring [programs for] us to consider, that it is legitimate. It’s been researched. They’re not just trying to throw money at a problem.”

Instruction Partners’ work at Newton was a success, Barrow told the Daily Yonder.

“You can tell teachers are thinking differently and deeper about what they’re doing in the classroom,” she said. “[Teacher planning] is 10 times better than it was before.”

This planning not only helps improve the school’s early literacy teaching, but teacher’s instructional skills in other subjects, Barrow said. She also said she sees her staff growing stronger and more unified, all of which may help with teacher retention — another top issue for many rural schools. 

“They feel the support,” Barrow said. “They’re not going to stay where they’re not supported if they can go and get [training opportunities] somewhere else.”

As for students: “Kids are the easy part,” Barrow said. “I don’t see a difference as far as how they accept it or interact. I see that deeper thinking that they’re doing … But kids are adaptable.”

Improving early literacy can also have positive effects on a student’s entire educational and professional journey, Fenton said.

“Better reading skills will only help you in all the other subjects and better work in science and social studies only helps your reading,” he said.

For other foundations or schools who serve rural communities, Rosser said the door is open. 

“We are very willing to talk to other rural funders and rural communities about how we’ve approached it,” he said. “Each of these ways we’re approaching [early literacy] could be adjusted for the local context in another rural region and it would be just as applicable.”

As for the East Texas region, the work to improve early literacy education carries on.

“We can’t have a thriving East Texas if our schools aren’t thriving,” Rosser said. “Everything that we’re doing is trying to ensure that young people can thrive, that families can thrive, that the region thrives.”
